<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written submission from Mr Stephen Evans MIET</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BRC26</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written submission from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Mr </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Stephen Evans</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">MIET</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">DCLG Electrical Competent Person Scheme</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I have watched the video from the HOC Communities and Local Government Committee meeting held on the 2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">nd</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> September 2013 and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">subsequently </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">submit my response to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">this below.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1. As I am broadly in agreement with what other contributors have so far submitted, I will refrain from repeating many of the points already raised. However, I would like to provide my views on the standards of training </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and changes to the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> regis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tration system.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">To briefly outline my knowledge of the industry, I am a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> electrician</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> with 40</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> years of experience and have worked</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in both commercial and domestic environments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Part P accredited</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> contractor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> when it was first introduced.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> I am a ful</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l member of the IET (institution of Engineering and Technology) and a registered electrician at technician grade with the JIB.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">During the last 7 years I have mainly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> worked</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as a freelance trainer for both private training providers and FE Colleges. This work has involved delivery of courses for industry recognised qualifications relating to the IET wiring regulations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (BS7671)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and Inspection and Testing. In addition, I am a q</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ualified NVQ assessor and verifier and have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">helped</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> many apprentices</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> achieve the Level 3 NVQ that is recognised within the industry as the minimum </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">standard of competency.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As has been pointed-out by other contributors, one of the negative </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">aspects</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of Part </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, which was initially welcomed by the trade as a way to improve standards,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> has been the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> way it’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> been hijacked by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> private training providers offering very short courses </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(at very high prices</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">anyone</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to become </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a domestic electrician</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  And whilst domesti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">c electrical systems are the least technically challenging,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> they still require a high level of compe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tency to be installed correctly and these</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> skills certainly can’t be learnt in just a few weeks</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Moreover, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to make matters worse, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">these short courses have be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">en encouraged by the various Part P scheme operators because they provide a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">good </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">source for new members and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">an easy way to boost</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> revenue</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Unfortunately, this is a classic case of a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> good idea having unintended consequences and t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he sad fact is that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> over</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">all</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">standards of domestic electrical installation work have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not improved at all and in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">many</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">instances</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> are actually worse</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  As mentioned above, I </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have worked</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for a private training company who provided these courses</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> witnessed first-hand the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">folly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of this policy.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In my opinion, and contrary to the wishes of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">current </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">accreditation bodies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> way forward is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">move away from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">profit based registration schemes and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">adopt a single </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">system of accreditation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> - which</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the public can easily unders</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tand</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">similar to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">gas industry </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">model</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (Gas Safe)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> -</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> whereby </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">ANY </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">individual working in the electrical industry must be suitably competent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and assessed on a regular basis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> It should also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">require all electricians to be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">suitably qualified to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">standards</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> recognised by the JIB</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ECS scheme,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> wh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ich</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, in addition to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">requiring the relevant </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">technical </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">certificates</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, require</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> proof of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> suitable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> experience</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I greatly welcome the DCLG </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">committee’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">investigation into this matter</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and strongly hope your conclusions are t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o recommend </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a root-and-branch overhaul </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of the current accreditation system </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> currently</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">benefits nobody except the scheme operators themselves.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> However, if this is not possible then</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> at the very least</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for the sake of clarity, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a single register</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">certified </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">installers should be adopted</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (or enforced by government) similar to that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> proposed by NAPIT</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">8. Finally, I was slightly dismayed that the committee did not challenge Emma Clancy’s claim that her organisation represents eighty percent of contractor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s who carry-out ninety percent of all electrical work. This may be true for the electrical contracting industry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as a whole</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DCLG committee </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is only considering the domestic market and I would be surprised if this percentage claim was so high in this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">segment of the industry?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I trust you will find my above contribution of interest and if you think I can be of further assistance please don’t hesitate to contact me.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">24</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> November 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>